      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Suburban Factor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Eric D Zimmerman letter contends development of outer suburbs leaves residents of these areas completely dependent on automobile transportation, adding to fuel price swings</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While general prosperity and the popularity of fuel-inefficient vehicles are partly responsible for the minimal drop in gasoline consumption (front page, Oct. 10), there is another contributing factor: millions more Americans now have no transportation alternatives.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While general prosperity and the popularity of fuel-inefficient vehicles are partly responsible for the minimal drop in gasoline consumption (front page, Oct. 10), there is another contributing factor: millions more Americans now have no transportation alternatives.</p>
        <p>Since the 1970's oil crisis, more and more outer suburban areas have been developed in a way that makes any form of transportation other than the private automobile impractical. Residents and workers in these areas do not have a choice between driving a car and using alternate transportation; their choice is between driving a car and staying home.</p>
        <p>Having created an infrastructure so inefficient that it requires people to move a ton of steel several miles to buy a quart of milk, is it any wonder that we have trouble responding to fuel price swings?</p>
        <p>ERIC D. ZIMMERMAN  New York, Oct. 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
